Commentary.Commentary: Update - 0642 IST (0112 GMT) - Lunch has been taken. The conditions are much better. Optimistic signs. An inspection will take place half an hour from now on.

Update - 0610 IST (0040 GMT) - It continues to drizzle and there are no improvements in conditions. The covers are firmly placed. Yet another dull start to the day. Fingers crossed for some positive updates.
Update - 0521 IST (2351 GMT) - The inspection is delayed further as our old foe has visited again. The covers are back on. Stay tuned as the rain continues to dominate this game.
Update - 0445 IST (2315 GMT) - Next pitch inspection is to happen half an hour from now on. Let's be optimistic.
The game should have probably started by now. There are no signs of rain right now but few showers are expected and due to excessive rain, there are some regions that have become muddy.

We expected a free flowing game between these two but the rain has played a big part till now. Welcome to action of Day 4 and the conditions are same today as well but hopefully we can expect some action. With so much rain we have forget where this match stands. Khawaja is stranded on 195 but looks like it will be the Proteas who will come out bat next. Stalemate looks the likeable option. However, let’s first hope for some action. Stay tuned.
...Day 4, Session 1...

The results are in from the umpires and they have called the end of Day 3. STUMPS. Not a single ball was bowled. It was predicted to be that kind of day but the next couple of days promise to give us some action. As it goes by, draw looks like the most possible result but we will let for you to decide. Join us again early on Day 4 at 0430 IST (1100 GMT, the previous day) for all the action. Till then, cheers!
Update - 1020 IST (0450 GMT) - It is still drizzling. Meanwhile, the umpires are out for an inspection. Looks like there will be an update shortly. Stay tuned.
Update - 0952 IST (0422 GMT) - Looks like Tea has been taken. The rain has stopped for now but no movements from the ground staff. Let's hope for some positive updates.
Update - 0845 IST (0315 GMT) - It is raining quite heavily now. The chances of any play look very dim.
Just here to say the situation is particularly the same. It is raining lightly but no signs of improvement.
No respite after the Lunch break as well. It's still pouring and the waiting game continues.
SOME REALLY GOOD NEWS! It has stopped raining and it should take around 30 minutes to get things ready. Early Lunch has been taken and if no more rain, we should have some play so after the break.
We have nothing new to update. The rain continues to fall and we continue to wait. Any kind of play today already seems a doubt. Fingers crossed though.
Well, we did mention that the forecast is not that great and we do not have the best of news to begin with as it is raining here and we might be in for a delayed start.

Welcome to the coverage of Day 3 of yet another Test dominated by the Aussies! Well, one can add rain too as it has played a big part so far. Just the 131 overs bowled in the two days completed and most of those have belonged to the hosts. They have yet again batted themselves into a position from where losing the game becomes almost improbable. Probably the declaration is around the corner, myabe immediately after Usman Khawaja gets to his double ton or after the cross the 500-run mark. South Africa on the other hand, probably have started to think about their batting which has not done so well thus far. Winning the game from here for them is probably out of contention but they would love to put on a better show with the bat and hopefully end this Test in a draw. The rain gods could also help them a little as the forecast isn't great for today. Let us hope the rain stays away though.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

Smith fell just after notching his 30th Test hundred. However, Travis Head who has been in form of his life came out with an aggressive approach and in no time scored his fifty. Usman Khawaja though was the architect of their innings. He is scoring centuries for fun lately. Talking about the tourists, they had very less assist from the pitch but even their discipline bowling didn't help against the mighty Aussies. The weather on Day 3 doesn't look good as well. However, we will bring you all the action. Join us at 0430 IST (1130 GMT, the previous day) and earlier for the build up. Till then, cheers!

Update - 1159 IST (0629 GMT) - The rain refuses to stop and that will be STUMPS on Day 2. What a day for Australia. You feel for Usman Khawaja who is stranded on 195. Although Australia haven't declared yet but you feel that this will be probably the end of their innings. He will hope for just one ball on Day 3 to get to the landmark. Let's recap Day 2 though. It was full of runs. Contributions from all the batters except David Warner and Australia are in a commanding position. Usman Khawaja was the mainstay right from the start. He along with Marnus Labuschagne added more than 100 first. The latter fall on the last ball of Day 1 but then Usman Khawaja joined hands with Steven Smith and that put South Africa on the back foot. They really had no answers to their show.

Update - 1135 IST (0605 GMT) - Drinks! South Africa want to change the ball and in the meantime, the drinks have been taken. This session is full of runs, Australia would be looking for another short phase with bat before asking South Africa to see out the final hurdle. Usman Khawaja on the other hand is eyeing 200. Ughhh! The rain has got a bit heavy and the PLAYERS ARE WALKING OFF.  The covers are on.

Update - 1022 IST (0452 GMT) - A bit of a delay to start this session as the rain has arrived. The covers are removed now and the mop up work is going on.
...Day 2, Session 3...

Yet again South Africa have not done anything wrong but Australia have been just too good with the bat. South Africa have been disciplined with their bowling but could be more aggressive with their field. Too many singles are not allowing any pressure to build. Anrich Nortje was bowling with intent again but it was Keshav Maharaj who took the only wicket in the session. Hard work continues for the tourists as they have to come back energetic for another big session with the ball.

Another session belongs to Australia. This session was full of runs and milestones. First, it was Khawaja with his 13th Test century and then Steven Smith with his brilliant 30th Test hundred. Smith though fell right after his 100 but Head looks calm and full of runs. Khawaja on the other hand will now eye for a double century. Australia are in a very good position. Probably we feel they'll bat for another session and score runs at the same rate.

South Africa toiled hard but with no reward! They though bowled quite a few freebies and leaked a lot more runs than they would have liked. The wicket has not offered a lot and the visitors are yet again pushed well and truly onto the back foot. They will need a few quick wickets after the break. Can they make use of the second new ball? We will find out.

A session which has belonged to the Aussies and there is no doubt about that! They have not lost a wicket and have managed to add above 100 runs. Both Steven Smith and Usman Khawaja came out with intent and scored freely. The wicket also seemed an easy paced one and the boundaries were flowing after the initial quiet phase. Both have added over 100 with Smith getting to his half ton and Usman Khawaja to his ton. Usman Khawaja's hundred was the highlight of the session and Australia will hope the two can keep batting and probably bat the visitors out of the game.

We managed just the 47 overs on Day 1 as rain played spoilt sport but those 47 overs were quite exciting. Australia would have been well in control had they not lost Marnus Labuschagne right before play was intervened by rain but we feel they still have their noses ahead thanks to the stand between Usman Khawaja and Marnus Labuschagne! The former is still going strong and Australia will hope, their in-form Steven Smith can give him good support and the two can put up another good stand. The visitors on the other hand, will hope that wicket of Marnus Labuschagne opens the floodgates and they can dominate the morning session here. Let us hope the rain stays away and we get a whole day's play.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 ...

South Africa on the other hand haven't done anything wrong. They bowled well but the host negotiated it well. Anrich Nortje bowled with intent and claimed both wickets. There isn't much to differentiate between both teams at this point with half of the day cleaned up due to bad light. Day 2 will start half an hour earlier at 0430 IST (1100 GMT, the previous day). Do join us for the build up as well. Cheers!

That will be Stumps on Day 1. It was inevitable. The light was not good enough to resume. So, we feel Australia will be happy in the end. Although they lost Marnus Labuschagne on the last ball, they dominated the day. Australia won the toss and made a good decision to bat first. They lost Warner early but the pair of Marnus Labuschagne and Usman Khawaja added 135-runs to steady things and take full control before bad light came into play.

Update - 1137 IST (0607 GMT) - Steven Smith walks out. However, has to walk off along with other players due to BAD LIGHT. It's that kind of day. The umpires are expecting some rain as the covers are coming on as well. It has started to rain.

OUT! EDGED AND GONE! Anrich Nortje gets the second wicket! The 135-run stand is broken! The break helps South Africa to find the breakthrough. This is serious pace from Nortje! Short of a length, angling around off before nipping away. Labuschagne gets on his toes as he tries to defend on the leg side with soft hands but the ball touches the shoulder of the bat and goes straight in the mitts of Kyle Verreynne. A fine innings from Marnus Labuschagne comes to an end.
Commentary.Howout: c Kyle Verreynne b Anrich Nortje

... DAY 1, SESSION 2 ...

A hard-fought session of Test cricket and one must say, the hosts will be the happier of the two sides but by just! It was not easy in the first session, the new ball did a bit and Australia lost Warner early but Usman Khawaja and Marnus Labuschagne did really well to weather that storm. The spinners though have begun well for the visitors but that too has been negotiated well by the two batters for now. The Aussies will hope the two can cash in after the break and put up a big stand. South Africa on the other hand, need to continue to be patient, the wicket is offering something for the bowlers and South Africa are bowling tidily but they will hope they get the rewards after the break. An interesting second session awaits.

Welcome to the coverage of the third and the last Test between South Africa and Australia! The action now shifts to Sydney, it has been one-way traffic so far as the hosts have dominated with both bat and ball. They will look for a whitewash with another win here. South Africa on the other hand, have been extremely poor so far but would want to end on a high. Can we have a competitive game? We will find out.
,,, MATCH DAY ...
We are back. The Aussie players are all set. Scorching heat in Sydney. Sarel Erwee and Dean Elgar to bat. They need to perform badly. Josh Hazlewood is ready to roar again.
...THIRD INNINGS...

The Proteas top order yet again failed to click. It was then Bavuma and Zondo who steadies the ship but they too fell after doing the hard work. South Africa ended Day 3 with 4 wickets still in hand and Australia would have thought they will run through easily but then came the big, stubborn partnership between Keshav Maharaj and Simon Harmer who stitched 85 runs with the former hitting a fifty. Once they both fell, Australia cleaned the tail quickly. Their bowlers though bowled superbly. Nathan Lyon bowled from one side for most of the time but it was their speed attack of Josh Hazlewood and Pat Cummins who did the hard work. The duo claimed 7 wickets together to put South Africa back with the bat in hand. Still, around 48 overs left. Let's see how much Australia have in the tank.

What a bowling performance from the Aussies! They haven't given up yet! AUSTRALIA HAVE ENFORCED THE FOLLOW-ON. South Africa still needed around 21 runs to avoid it. This gun bowling performance still has enough energy left to take all 10 wickets again. What an interesting match this is turning out to be.

The Aussies tried everything, all their bowlers bowled decent lines and lengths but they just were not rewarded. They though will hope they can somehow get the remaining wickets quickly. Join us for the second session which is also another important one.

That will the first aim for the visitors, to avoid the follow-on.

Welcome to the coverage of the last day of the last Test of this series between the Aussies and South Africa. Despite all the rain around, we still head into the last day with a chance of a result. However, there is only one team which has a realistic chance of winning and that is the hosts. Their bowlers though will have to be at their best if they are to force a result. 14 wickets is what they will need to take in a day if they are to do so and it is well and truly possible considering how the visitors have batted in this series so far. However, the away side will be keen to not finish on the losing side. Despite all the overs we have lost, this could well be an exciting finish. The first session could probably decide which way this game is heading towards.
... DAY 5, SESSION 1 ...

South Africa were pushed back with three quick wickets. Bavuma and Zondo started the repair work but both gave away wickets to some energetic bowling. The visitors now have lost their batters but the bowling all-rounders have made sure they end the day without losing any more wickets. Jansen and Harmer have closed the day well however, Australia will be fired up once again as they push for the win. Credit goes to how Pat Cummins and co. bowled today. The skipper himself turned up with a fiery spell. Nathan Lyon too extracted some turn. What looked like this match will end certainly in a draw, Australia have made this dull game filled with rain, end for an entertaining purpose. Join us for the final day, on Day 5 at 0430 IST (2300 GMT, the previous day). Do join us for the build up. Cheers!

What a lively end to a disappointing day! After four-straight sessions had been washed out, no one saw this game grow at such a rapid pace. Australia are clearly favorites to win but realistically they need wickets and wickets to win. South Africa on the other end are wobbling but need to hang in there to survive. South Africa still need to score 126 more runs to avoid the follow-on.

... DAY 4, FINAL SESSION ...

A profitable session for the home side. Questions would have been asked regarding Cummins' declaration with Khawaja on 195, but Australia's bowlers have made the fans forget that pain to some extent. They have come out with venom and once again, blown away the opposition's top order. In the context of the match, it may not count for much as a draw looms very large but in terms of confidence going into India, that is a big yes.  Every Australian bowler barring Agar has looked threatening and if there is a slight ray of hope for a result, then Australia need to get the Proteas out tonight. Possible? Too steep? Fightback? Stay tuned for the final session...

Pat Cummins calls his team members as the trophy is handed over to him. That concludes the presentation. The Aussie players pose for the camera. Clean-sweep from Australia. They are certainly in the finals of the World Test Championship, not yet but certainly. That is all from us. Hope you enjoyed the coverage. An action-packed cricketing schedule is lined up. Keep checking the schedule page. Till then, it is goodbye and cheers!

Pat Cummins, the captain of Australia says the wicket was good and hoped for wickets in this match. Adds it was a really good batting surface but his team gave all. Applauds the performance of Lyon. Tells it was pleasing to see everyone contribute with bat and ball. On the tour against India, says they will regroup and are looking forward to it. Reckons he is happy with his performance.

Dean Elgar, the skipper of South Africa says it is never easy to play against the Aussies. Adds the message was to fight till the end. Shares there were learning for many players. Credits to Pat Cummins and his team for how they played. Adds there are many positives from this series. Says Test cricket teaches resilience to wake up the next day and fight again. Tells it was a rollercoaster of a series. Says he is short of runs but hopes to comeback strong.

David Warner wins the PLAYER OF THE SERIES award. The opener says it was a fantastic performance from the whole team but credits the bowler to showcase intent in this match and go for the win. Applauds the performance of Anrich Nortje and how the Proteas played. Shares that they tried their best but South Africa's tail-enders hold on. On the next tour to India, he says it is a massive challenge and they are looking forward to it.

Usman Khawaja wins the Player of the Match. He feels there have been ups and downs in his career, it's been tough at times but rewarding on the other side as well. Says patience was key on this pitch. On missing the double-ton, he says it is about winning and Australia showed it is team first every time. He says South Africa played well, they are a tough team to beat.

Steven Smith is up for a chat. He says they tried to win but few of the umpire's calls didn't go their way. Feels things could have been different. Shares that he cannot do much about the catches which went upstairs to check. Tells he is happy to score some runs before going to India.

No doubt Australia were the better team with both bat and ball. In the first match at the Gabba, on a tricky pitch, the bowlers made the most of it but it was Travis Head's counterattacking approach which was the difference. At Melbourne, we saw Cameron Green take five wickets but the star of the game was David Warner who scored 200. Fine contributions from Smith, Head and Green and Carey's 100 helped Australia win by an innings. Green and Starc missed out on the last match due to injuries but there was no short of intent from the Aussies.

Australia gave a hefty target and Pat Cummins and co. gave their all from the word go with the ball. South Africa were in a sort of trouble at one stage but contributions from Bavuma, Zondo and later fifty from Keshav Maharaj and a fine knock from Simon Harmer steadied the ship. It was the pace duo of Cummins and Hazlewood who claimed wickets together. Australia with less than 50 overs to play on the final day enforced follow-on, hoping for a miracle and looking for a win but the Proteas batters in their second innings showed great resilient to conclude with a draw.

Rain played a big part in the game or else there was definitely a winner with the tides more often to the host's shore. Australia made a good decision by batting first. Usman Khawaja was the architect of their batting with Marnus Labuschagne, Smith and Head playing hand from the other side. Usman Khawaja though was left stranded on 195 as the rain came in and swiped more than four sessions.

Draw it is! A fair result in the end! We feel the stand between Keshav Maharaj and Simon Harmer concluded this into a draw. However, till the last hour, Australia pushed for the win. The Aussie bowlers gave their all but it was just too big an ask from them. Australia win the series by 2-0.

...Day 5, Final Session...

South Africa have weathered the storm pretty well. The pitch is getting better to bat on. Australia need more than enough to extract a win now we feel. Heinrich Klaasen and Sarel Erwee have done well to calm things down and score runs when given any free balls. Around 30 overs remaining now. Australia need 9 wickets to win. The session saw The Aussie bowlers first clean up the tail. They enforced the follow-on and Pat Cummins again got his man, Elgar down the leg side. However, South Africa are looking comfortable but don't take this Australian team lightly. They need a couple of deliveries to turn the tides back. Stay tuned for the final session of this match.
